<h2>What Body Image Is and When It Becomes a Problem</h2>
<p>Body image is the mental picture you have of your body — how you perceive, think about, and feel about your physical appearance. Negative body image involves persistent dissatisfaction with how you look, distorted perception of your appearance, and significant distress or functional impairment related to appearance concerns.</p>

<p>Body image sits on a spectrum. At one end, common appearance dissatisfaction that most people experience sometimes. At the other, Body Dysmorphic Disorder (BDD) — a clinically significant condition in which perceived appearance flaws (often minor or imagined) consume hours per day, cause severe distress, and drive repetitive behaviours like checking, camouflaging, or reassurance-seeking.</p>

<h2>How Negative Body Image Develops</h2>
<p>Body image is not innate — it's constructed from years of social input, comparison, media exposure, and interpersonal feedback. Risk factors include:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Weight-based teasing or bullying in childhood or adolescence</li>
  <li>Diet culture exposure and internalisation of unrealistic appearance ideals</li>
  <li>Social comparison on social media</li>
  <li>Comments from caregivers about weight, food, or appearance</li>
  <li>Sexual trauma or objectification</li>
  <li>Cultural messages about bodies in particular ethnic, religious, or community contexts</li>
</ul>

<h2>The Psychological Mechanisms</h2>
<p>Negative body image is maintained by several cognitive and behavioural mechanisms:</p>

<p><strong>Distorted perception:</strong> People with significant body image issues often literally perceive their bodies inaccurately — overestimating size, magnifying certain features. This isn't vanity; it's a genuine perceptual distortion.</p>

<p><strong>Appearance-contingent self-worth:</strong> When self-esteem is contingent on looking a certain way, appearance concerns become existential — threatening the entire sense of self rather than just how one looks.</p>

<p><strong>Safety behaviours:</strong> Checking mirrors compulsively, avoiding photos, wearing concealing clothing, seeking reassurance — these behaviours are attempts to manage anxiety but actually maintain it.</p>

<p><strong>Avoidance:</strong> Avoiding social situations, intimacy, certain clothing, exercise, or any context that activates body anxiety reduces quality of life and reinforces the idea that one's appearance is shameful or dangerous.</p>

<h2>Evidence-Based Treatment</h2>

<h3>CBT for Body Image</h3>
<p>CBT targets the cognitive distortions (inaccurate self-perception, appearance-contingent worth) and the behavioural maintenance factors (safety behaviours, avoidance). It includes mirror exposure (learning to view the body neutrally), reducing checking behaviours, challenging unhelpful comparisons, and broadening self-worth beyond appearance.</p>

<h3>CBT for BDD</h3>
<p>BDD requires a specific CBT protocol with significant ERP (exposure and response prevention) components, targeting the compulsive checking, camouflaging, and reassurance-seeking that maintain the condition. It has good evidence.</p>

<h3>Acceptance-Based Approaches</h3>
<p>ACT and body-neutral approaches shift the goal from feeling good about your appearance to disengaging from the appearance-evaluation loop entirely — pursuing what matters regardless of how you feel about how you look. This is particularly valuable when the goal of "positive body image" feels impossible or forced.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<p><strong>Is body image therapy different from eating disorder treatment?</strong><br/>
They overlap significantly — negative body image is central to eating disorders. Body image-focused therapy addresses the appearance concerns specifically; eating disorder treatment additionally addresses disordered eating behaviours and their physical consequences.</p>

<p><strong>Can social media avoidance help?</strong><br/>
Research shows that reducing social media — particularly image-heavy platforms — is associated with improved body image. It's a useful adjunct but not a treatment on its own. The underlying cognitions remain.</p>

